equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives leucine prediction through structural contact reading
equation_narrative.story: Position 15 in ubiquitin sits in a hydrophobic core environment, surrounded by 6 structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation of this buried, hydrophobic context by reading local sequence and structural neighbors. The logit lens reflects this hydrophobic character, showing early prominence of valine and tyrosine before settling toward branched-chain aliphatics. At layer 24-25, the decision phase begins: leucine-specific prediction channels activate, and the model commits. By layer 30, leucine reaches 41.6% probability and wins decisively at 48.0%, with phenylalanine emerging late as runner-up at 27.6%.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and local context. The model reads 6 structural contacts through attention heads, establishing a hydrophobic environment. Early layers (1-9) show high-projection features (F1:5480, F9:5728 with 45-56 proj) encoding position identity and local sequence. The logit lens trajectory reflects the representation's hydrophobic character: valine peaks at 48.7% at layer 24, while leucine gradually rises from 13.7% (L0) to 21.9% (L23). Lead changes between Y, H, K, A, and V in layers 1-16 reflect shifting representation character as different aspects of the context accumulate—not prediction attempts. By layer 18, the representation stabilizes around branched-chain hydrophobic residues (L, V, I collectively ~55%), consistent with a buried core position.
perception_phase.context_character: The assembled context by L23 is strongly hydrophobic and buried: 6 structural contacts, local sequence rich in hydrophobic residues (KTIT[?]EVEP), and representation features consistent with core-packing constraints. No significant co-evolutionary signal (only 2 coevolving positions) suggests local structural determinism dominates.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within contact distance, read primarily through attention heads at L29-32 (head 0 at L29 with 1.352 proj, structural_attn=0.226)
Local sequence: Strong local attention at L12 (head 12, 1.397 proj, local_attn=0.874) and L28-29 (heads 18 and 10 with 1.52 and 1.726 proj)
Minimal co-evolutionary coupling: only 2 coevolving positions, indicating local context dominates over distant functional constraints
Early features: F1:5480 (45.3 proj) and F9:5728 (55.7 proj) encode position identity and local hydrophobic environment

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at layers 24-26. Layer 25 shows the strongest velocity event (+6.19 total_delta, attention-driven), where leucine jumps from 21.9% to 36.9%. MLP neurons at L24-26 contribute +2.52 proj, with specific L-voting neurons activating (N24:4188 with 0.433 proj, N25:1424 with 0.474 proj). Leucine continues rising through L29-31 (reaching 47.1% at L31) before final MLP adjustments at L32-33. Phenylalanine emerges late, jumping from 6.0% at L29 to 27.6% at L33, driven by late-layer aromatic prediction channels.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the perception-to-decision shift. At L23, valine leads at 39.4% with leucine at 21.9%—still reflecting hydrophobic representation character. At L24, valine spikes to 48.7% (its peak) but leucine-specific features begin activating (F24:8316 with 16.6 proj). By L25, attention-driven velocity (+3.72 attn_delta) and MLP neurons (N25:1424, N25:2189) push leucine to 36.9%, marking the first true prediction commitment.

candidates.narrative: Leucine wins through sustained MLP support in the decision phase. At L24-26, leucine-voting neurons activate (N24:4188 0.433 proj, N25:1424 0.474 proj, N26:2219 0.466 proj), driving probability from 21.9% to 36.9%. Layer 29 brings the strongest single boost: N29:2073 fires with 1.111 proj (the highest single-neuron contribution), pushing leucine to 41.6%. Despite late competition from phenylalanine and a dip at L32-33 (MLP erasure of -4.55), leucine stabilizes at 48.0% final probability.
candidates.key_layers: Commits at L25, peaks at L31 (47.1%), stabilizes at L33 (48.0%)
key_evidence: N29:2073 (1.111 proj) — strongest single leucine-voting neuron, fires at critical L29
N25:1424 (0.474 proj) and N27:4924 (0.695 proj) — sustained MLP support through decision phase
Attention at L25 (+3.72 attn_delta) and L30 (+5.78 attn_delta) — structural context integration

candidates.narrative: Phenylalanine emerges explosively in the final layers, rising from 6.0% at L29 to 27.6% at L33. This late surge is driven by aromatic prediction channels activating after the core hydrophobic decision is made. F30:5194 (54.8 proj) and F33:9048 (92.1 proj) are high-projection attention features that fire strongly in the final layers. The model appears to recognize that aromatic residues (F, Y) can also occupy hydrophobic cores, but this signal arrives too late to overcome leucine's established lead.
candidates.key_layers: Minimal until L29 (6.0%), surges L30-33 to 27.6%
key_evidence: F30:5194 (attn, 54.8 proj) — aromatic prediction channel activates at L30
F33:9048 (attn, 92.1 proj) — strongest final-layer feature, aromatic-specific

candidates.narrative: Valine dominates the logit lens through the perception phase, peaking at 48.7% at layer 24. This reflects the representation's strong branched-chain hydrophobic character—valine is chemically similar to leucine and fits the assembled context. However, valine is not a prediction but a representation artifact. Once leucine-specific neurons activate at L25-26, valine declines sharply (48.7% → 21.4% → 11.1%), losing to leucine's more specific MLP support. The model distinguishes between V and L based on subtle packing preferences encoded in late-layer neurons.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L14-L28, peaks at L24 (48.7%), collapses L28-33
key_evidence: Representation character: V reflects assembled hydrophobic context, not model belief
Loses to L-specific MLP neurons at L25-29 (N29:2073 votes L>>V)

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine tracks closely with leucine through the perception phase (8.7% at L17, 10.1% at L23) as another branched-chain hydrophobic option. It peaks at 22.0% at layer 31, briefly competitive with leucine. However, isoleucine lacks the strong MLP neuron support that leucine receives—no I-specific neurons with >0.3 proj appear in the top writers. The model's final discrimination between L and I likely depends on beta-branching preferences that favor leucine in this specific structural context.
candidates.key_layers: Rises L17-L31 (8.7% → 22.0%), fades to 11.4% at L33
key_evidence: Peaks at L31 (22.0%) but lacks decisive MLP support
No high-projection I-specific neurons in decision phase

candidates.narrative: Tyrosine shows a dramatic early spike, peaking at 39.3% at layer 6 before collapsing to <1% by layer 17. This early prominence reflects aromatic/polar features in the initial representation—possibly from reading nearby threonine (T14) or the local sequence context. However, as structural contacts are integrated (layers 8-16), the representation shifts decisively toward aliphatic hydrophobic character, and tyrosine's logit-lens projection vanishes. This is a classic example of early representation instability: Y's prominence is not a prediction but an artifact of incomplete context assembly.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L6 (39.3%), collapses by L17 (0.65%)
key_evidence: Representation shift: aromatic features give way to aliphatic as structural context loads
Final probability 0.69% — completely rejected after perception phase

turning_points.description: The representation undergoes a major chemical shift. Tyrosine collapses from 39.3% (L6) to 21.4% (L8) as the model integrates structural information. Lead changes from Y to Q to H reflect unstable early features—the representation is still assembling basic context. This is perception-phase turbulence, not decision-making. By layer 9, features like F9:5728 (55.7 proj) stabilize the representation toward hydrophobic character.

The representation crystallizes around branched-chain hydrophobic residues. Leucine takes the logit-lens lead at L13 (18.9%), and by L17 the L+V+I trio accounts for ~55% of the lens projection. Attention at L13 (+2.54 attn_delta, driven by head 12) integrates local sequence context. This marks the end of early instability—the model has assembled a coherent hydrophobic-core representation.

The decision phase begins. Layer 24 shows valine's final peak (48.7%) before leucine-specific neurons activate. Layer 25 delivers the decisive push: attention (+3.72 attn_delta) and MLP (+2.47 mlp_delta) combine for +6.19 total velocity toward leucine. N25:1424 (0.474 proj) and N25:2189 (0.349 proj) vote strongly for L. By L26, leucine leads at 38.9% and never relinquishes control. This is where perception becomes prediction.

Leucine solidifies its victory through massive MLP support. N29:2073 fires with 1.111 proj—the single strongest leucine vote in the entire network—pushing L from 36.9% to 41.6%. Layer 30 adds attention-driven support (+5.78 attn_delta), and L31 brings additional MLP neurons (N31:1920 with 0.666 proj, N31:4490 with 0.627 proj). Leucine peaks at 47.1% at L31. Meanwhile, phenylalanine begins its late surge (6.0% → 15.5%), setting up the final competition.

deep_dives.caption: Layer 12 head 12 (1.397 proj, local_attn=0.874) and layer 13 attention (+2.54 attn_delta) integrate local sequence. This is where the representation stabilizes around branched-chain hydrophobic character.

deep_dives.caption: Features at L18 show the fully assembled hydrophobic representation. F18:7108 (6.71 proj) and F18:4885 (6.56 proj) encode the structural context that will guide the decision phase.

deep_dives.caption: Watch leucine-specific neurons activate. N24:4188 (0.433 proj), N25:1424 (0.474 proj), and N26:2219 (0.466 proj) cast the first decisive votes for leucine, overcoming valine's logit-lens dominance.

deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP push. N29:2073 (1.111 proj) is the strongest single leucine vote. L30-31 add sustained support (N30:416, N31:1920, N31:4490) that locks in the prediction.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels (L30, L33)
deep_dives.caption: High-projection features at L30 (F30:5194 with 54.8 proj) and L33 (F33:9048 with 92.1 proj) show the final prediction state. Note the late aromatic signal (F-specific) that drives phenylalanine's surge.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts leucine by assembling a hydrophobic core context through structural contact reading (6 contacts) and local sequence integration (layers 8-17), then activating leucine-specific MLP neurons in the decision phase (L24-31). The strongest evidence is N29:2073's 1.111 projection—the single most decisive vote for leucine—combined with sustained MLP support at L25-31 (total +2.52 to +3.16 proj across layers). Phenylalanine's late surge (27.6% final) shows the model recognizes aromatic residues can occupy hydrophobic cores, but this signal arrives too late to overcome leucine's established lead. The prediction succeeds because the assembled structural context (buried, hydrophobic, beta-branched preference) precisely matches leucine's chemical profile.
